segments.text: Well, some of the older Army types were skeptical, but I think they all recognized the right thing to do and the right move.
Of course, they would have rather had it under their command.
Sure.
And they now have their own Air Corps again.
Sure.
But there wasn't, you and an instructor at West Point, there wasn't any tension?
No, because we're getting graduates from West Point who are going into the Air Corps every year.
Sure.
And from the Naval Academy as well at that time until we established the Air Corps together.
Sure.
All right.
You were on again and off again at West Point.
You were there from May of 46 to September of 47.
Well, what I did was I went to Springfield College and got my master's degree in physical education.
Oh, okay.
That's just what I thought.
You were there at Springfield College from September of 47 to June of 48, basically.
Yeah.
I just got my master's degree.
And why did you pick Springfield College?

my predecessor had gone there and it was recognized at that time it was recognized as the best physical education school in the United States and it's I don't know that it is still it's the old YMCA what it is the YMCA college it's had a physical education program that
outstanding program for years and most of the leaders in the physical education field have been graduates or have attended and gotten their graduate degrees from there.
How did you like it there?
I enjoyed it.
It was very difficult because I had
carried a heavy, heavy load of subjects.
My wife was pregnant.
We had one small child.
We rented an apartment and had stoked the furnace.
I'd get up at 5 o'clock in the morning and stoke the furnace and feed them both breakfast because she couldn't stand the smell of cooking.
And then I'd come home.
She had morning sickness?
No, the smell of cooking made her sick.
Oh.
She was miserable, I think.
And I would leave and go to school and be there all day and get home about 6.
And then feed them dinner and study until about 12 o'clock and stoke the furnace.
It was like a long grind.
It was, but I enjoyed it.
And you received your master's.
Well, I didn't receive it then.
I finished the courses.
I had to write a thesis.
After I wrote the thesis, I didn't get it until it was done, until it was 51.
And had anything changed, or did you basically continue for the next two years to teach the same courses?

Well, the first year, I had been in charge of, I had been the S4 for the office, which was in charge of Office 5, and in charge of the gymnasiums, all the facilities, and the cleaning up, and all that.
In the last two years, I was the operations officer.
I did all the scheduling, looked up all the schedules.
So it was a different job, although I didn't change anything when I was teaching.
You left West Point in July of 1950, and for six months you were a student at Maxwell Air Force Base.
Yeah, the Air Command Staff College.
Tell me about that.
That's the intermediate level of the Air Force of the Air University, the Air Force Educational System.
And that's to teach staff level people to do staff level duties and to broaden their

aspects of it and look at the Air Force from a different viewpoint and whatever they're using narrowly then like you've done a fighter pilot all the time just to spread you across so you can look at the full perspective and look at all the
look at what the material officer does, what the office officer does, what the personnel officer does, what they all do, and prepare them for high-level staff and command duty.
So this was exactly what it was for.
How good was it?
It was excellent.
Very good.
Was it primarily based on the Army command and general staff?
I don't know what the Army Command and General Staff had.
It was developed by the Air University.
And your instructors were mostly colonels?
I wouldn't say that they were mostly colonels.
Mostly lieutenant colonels and colonels.
How was the quality of instruction?
The quality was outstanding.
Very well done.
They've done a good job forming the Air University and getting it stocked with good people.
And why then after your completion in December 1950 did you become the Assistant Secretary and then the Secretary of the Air University?
Well... For the next three years?
Almost.
It picked me off.
Well, a guy that had known me was a secretary.
I had nothing.
Every major command, there's a shot at whoever was a graduate there.
They have a shot at selecting who they want.
I guess they had enough.
They selected me.
Put me in there.
Well, why you?
Were you an outstanding student?
Well, I was a good student, yes, but I don't know why me any more than anybody else.
They looked at my record to see where I'd been and what I'd done, I suppose.
They also gave you a promotion to Lieutenant Colonel at the time, in 1950.
Well, that promotion probably came from my
performance of the military community, probably.
A lot of people during this time were not being promoted at all, because of the United States, well from 45 to 50 we were decreasing, and you get an appointment
I think it was more than a record.
It probably had to do with the record and the particular age group or group of people that I was with in the rank of major.
I've been a major since 44.
This was temporary promotion.
I guess I was in the eligible group and got selected.
Were you eager to go to France?
I sure was.
I volunteered for it.
I wrote a letter.
I knew the director of personnel, officer personnel in Pentagon.
I wrote a letter volunteering.
And that's the way I got to go.
And what did he...
Well, you didn't go until September of 1953.
Well, I had to be jet qualified, and then I had to check out in the airplanes.
Okay.
Well, before we talk about jet qualifying, which, of course, in April of 1953, you get the jet course, tell me what you did as the assistant secretary and secretary of the Air University.
What does it mean?
What were your duties?
I had charge of all the records of all the students in the Air University.
So you're like a registrar.
Yeah, like a registrar.
And I worked for the Director of Education.
And I wrote all his letters and composed them.
And I wrote all the letters to all the guest speakers for the Air War College, Air Command Staff College, where they were getting the guest speakers.
And I provided for their billeting, their transportation, and we met them.
It sounds pretty much like a fighter pilot at a desk job.
It sure was.
What did you think of it?
I wasn't very happy.
Well, I enjoyed it all right, but I'd rather be in a flying organization.
I figured I'd learn something.
What did you learn?
I learned a lot about the Air Force by George Kenny, the commander.
I wrote letters for his signature.
He told me a lot of his experiences.
I had another guy named Barker, who was the vice commander.
I learned a lot from him.
about Hannon people.
And my boss, of course, director of education, third down in command.
Non-rated officer.
He was a very brilliant man.
Very articulate.
Inspiring.
You must have had a lot of very important guests come to your university and talk.
I had to run the Board of Visitors, too.
It's a very prestigious group.
We have Notre Dame.
We have MIT.
We have Georgia Tech.
You name it.
One time or another, they come down and evaluate the whole education system.
Which is one reason why I think it's so good.
Because it has had top level attention.
I mean top range in the country in terms of education.
So it was a good blend.
I mean you got a lot of advice and gave advice too to civilians.
Yes.
Nice.
Did you have a good working relationship?
Beautiful working relationship.
With the civilians?
With the civilians.
It was outstanding.
They were real, they were enthusiastic about it.
And it helped a lot too.
In what way?
Recommendations.
Sure.
On improved quality of education.
How to improve the quality of the education.
So it doesn't seem to me that there was any tension between the military officers running their educational institution and the university civilians.
No.
Very cooperative.
As a matter of fact, one of the schools at the Arizona University has a degree granting authorization.
Which one?
The Air Force Institute of Technology at Black Patterson.
They give degrees in engineering, aeronautical engineering, and graduate degrees, too.
Fantastic.
That really is.
Were you happy to get to that jet course in April of 1953?
I was elated.
That's what I had worked for.
I volunteered for them.
Okay, now tell me about this from April of 1953 to August of 1953.
What type of jets were you using?
FASXs?
Well, I checked out.
I did a qualification course in the T-33 at Craig Air Force Base.
I was part of the training command at that time.
Then I went to Nellis Air Force Base and started out by qualifying in the F-80 and diabolomic strafing and combat tactics and so forth.
And then went into the F-86.
Qualified in the F-86.
Theoretically went over there to be in an F-86 organization.
But when I got there, this year's commander put me in as director of safety for the 7th Air Force.
5th Air Force.
What was your opinion of that mode, being director of safety?
I didn't want it, but I didn't have any choice, so I just went in and did the best job I could.
What did you think of flying jets?
This must have been your first time, wasn't it?
Yes, I enjoyed it.
It was completely different because you forgot about TARC.
You didn't have to worry about TARC.
You didn't have to worry about takeoff control.
The acceleration is not there that you have on a prop aircraft.
The acceleration of the airplane is low speed.
And the reaction is not the same.
It's harder to fly formation, again, when you tend to over-control the throttle.
But it's a great advance in aviation in these aircraft.
What about as far as the armaments, the firepower of the F-86 versus those P-47s?
Well, there's no comparison to the F-86s.
So much more firepower than the other F-86s.
Just all the difference in the world.
Now, when you got to Korea, the war was almost over.
Yeah, the war was there.
But I did get into the 86 for a while.
You did get to do some flying in February of 54 and May of 54.
You were the commander of the 18th bomb group.
Fighter bomber.
Yeah, fighter bomber group in Korea.
You didn't get to go on any missions because by that time
The war was over by that time.
Yeah, but I did get to do some experimental missions.
Oh, really?
Tell me about those.
They had some planes coming down at night, and so we ran an experiment, the F-86, to try to get on the tail of one of these with radar.
get up close enough so you could eyeball it and shoot them down.
We never were able to get it all together.
What do you mean you weren't able to?
Well, we had to be ready to go and then they would scramble you off and vector you in by radar onto the tail of the airplane.
Then you get close enough to eyeball it and shoot it down.
They never were able to vector, keep the low-level aircraft on their scope enough to give us enough perspective to give him enough time so that we could intercept it.
How'd you get along with the Koreans?
Did you fly at all with any of the Korean Air Force, or didn't they have jets at this time?
We got along fine with them.
I don't think we had jets at that time.
Did you fly any joint missions with them?
No.
How about with other U.N. forces?
We had a squadron of South Africans.
They went home.
How'd you get along with them?
Great.
They were terrific people.
Very enthusiastic.
They were pretty wild.
Wild in what way?
Well, they liked to party.
They had their own little club.
They had arm wrestling, leg wrestling.
Oh, kidding.
Yeah.
And, uh, corrals.
They really sang and acted like Zulu warriors.
Did they get along pretty well?
Yes, they got along great.
That's what they were like.
And we also had some Australians on the legs, too.
They were real nice, too.
How were they?
Were they as well trained as we were in America?
Well, I really had no access to their abilities, except that they flew well.
Seemed to be well trained.
Okay.
Speaking of South Africans,
And during the war in Korea, of course, we did integrate the forces, ship from segregated units to integrated units.
Did this have any impact on the Air Force when you were over in Korea?
Not really.
Dan Davis came over and took over one of the wings.
I inspected him and gave him a safety inspection.
He's a close friend of mine.
I like him.
No problem.
He had no race problems?
They may have had some in the Army, but we didn't have any aircraft.
Oh, really?
Well, I don't know.
There were quite a few.
There were several that Steve had.
We had had in the war, hadn't we?
There were quite a few.
I don't have any feel for the numbers, but there were quite a few.
Oh, is your opinion that Truman's move to integrate the armed forces?
I think he was right.
Probably.

think we should be okay of course it came much earlier than the rest of the society and some some officers charged at the time back in 48 that the at the air force the military the armed forces in general uh were being or shouldn't be the social engineers for the rest of the society did you hear any of this
No, not really.
You thought it was a good move, though?
I thought it was a good move.
OK. Also during the mid-1950s, there was the rise of the Strategic Air Command.
And other Air Force officers have told me that there was some feelings of Air Force officers who weren't with SAC about that command.
No, I think it's very necessary command, and I think it was handled well, and they did give them a priority that enabled them to get what they got, but that's what it took to get it.
They did neglect the tactical air command, which they did or did not.
They did in favor of the strategic air command, but that was understandable in my opinion because the tactical air command is support for the Army.
And what we needed was strategic air, which we didn't have, and we needed.
That's the way we got it.
Although I didn't want to be in the security command, I think it's proven its effectiveness and its usefulness.
Why didn't you want to be in it?
I wanted to be a fire pilot, not a bomber pilot.
You yourself never felt tense or anxious about the fact that SAC was getting
higher priority than TAC?
Well, I may have had a little feeling about that, but I saw the reason for it.
It didn't upset me, because I did see the reason.
How about the other fighter pilots?
Did they see the reason?
No.
Was there tension between TAC and SAC?
I don't know about tension.
It may have been resentment.
Do you remember any examples of resentment?
I don't know.
Specific examples, no.
OK, and hard.
That's hard to think back and think of specifically.
I've heard opinions of us at the Air University.
What was their opinion?
By TAC members, these are the SACs.
What was the general feeling at the Air University?
Well, the Air University was far-sighted all the way.
probably the origins thing.
Well, of course, during this period, TV movies were glamorizing the Strategic Air Command.
There were a couple of movies about these dashing young bomber pilots and their role in the mission.
Did this create any jealousy or hard feelings in TAC?
I don't think so.
Did you see any of those movies?
I doubt it.
I don't go to movies.
Okay.
Also at this time, 53, you became a full colonel.
What were your feelings when you heard that?
I didn't believe it.
Why not?
I don't know.
Well, competition was pretty keen.
It sure is.
It is and was.
Very keen.
That's not to say I wasn't extremely pleased and happy.
Well, you always think there's a possibility.
The probability is quite small.
Selection, you've got more competition to be a general and a colonel than you do anywhere else.
Okay.
Here we are in 1954, and you have a series of assignments.
Arbitration Committee.
Oh, that's what I...
I was moved and I was sent to... Nellis Air Force Base.
I was sent home early to be on the representative for the Far Eastern Air Command on the Arbitration Committee for the Fighter Reference.
Not much of a job.
It was only a month.
Well, you know, you're just there during the exercises, during the competition.
And then what do you do, basically grade the competition?
No, the arbitration committee solves disputes and questions of rules and regulations and protests and the final determination of who's the winner.
How did you like that type of assignment?
It wasn't much of an assignment.
It was a boondocking for it, I was concerned.
I stayed in Las Vegas.
Oh, did you in Las Vegas?
No, I stayed out at the base because you could go to Las Vegas every night.
That sounds like more fun than work.
It was more fun than work.
Okay, so then you had another quick assignment in Texas, the advanced flying school.
Well, I went to Perrin Air Force Base as the group commander, and they sent me through the F-86 flying school, the F-86D, which is the interceptor.
So I just went through the course.
And then you became the commander of the group, training group.
Of the training group.
And you did that for about a year and a half, from October 54 to January 1956.
Now, what were major challenges at that job?
Well, the F-86D was a complicated electronic machine.
And we were also trying to determine how well the weapon system worked.
And we did a lot of evaluation of the firing system down at Matagorda Island.
And we were able to get our airplanes combat ready.
They were able to fire the rockets and hit the target.
The challenge was to qualify the students.
How many students did you usually have in a class?
Gee, that's hard to remember.
I think we were around 50.
40 to 50 students per class, and you'd have about three classes there at a time.
One would be in academics, one would be in instrument training, and the other one would be in .
I gave her instrument training in .
Because this was an all-weather aircraft.
And we qualified everybody.
Even though we already had an estimate card, we re-qualified to make sure they could fly in a jet aircraft.
Because we got some people who had not been particularly experienced in jet aircraft.
Sure.
And then we checked them out every six.
And we had a flying crew there, too.
Because you had earlier schools checking you out back in the 40s on prop planes, and now here you are checking other people out on jet planes.
What kind of changes did the Air Force have to make?
I mean, did they increase the length of the school?
Yes, we increased the ground school part of it.
Familiarization with the airplane was a lot longer and much more complicated.
more complicated systems.
Sure.
And you had to understand how the systems work and how they relate to each other.
And to know when an airplane was safe to fly and when it wasn't safe to fly.
And also what the emergency procedures are, what you do if this fails or that fails.
And we also had simulator, which
We had completely new technology.
And you could put the guy under the hood and have him take the airplane off and land it without effort.
And he could simulate a complete mission.
I bet you that.
Intercept training and everything else.
We'd give him intercept training.
Right in the simulator?
Right in the simulator, which is an innovation at that time.
I bet.
And now we've got it in all of them.
Sure, but isn't it?
At that time, it was a real innovation.
So you probably had very low amount or percentage of crashes by the 50s after the simulator than in the 40s, is that true?
That's true.
As a matter of fact, safety has been a prime mission of the Air Force.
Sure, absolutely.
And in comparison with your command at the training group, in comparison with other training groups in the country, how was your accident rate?
Well, I don't know how it was compared with it.
But didn't they give you comparative figures?
Oh, yes, they gave you comparative figures, but I sure as heck can't remember.
Oh.
The accident rate in the F-86D was fairly high per flying hour, because that's the way they measure.
There's so many accidents per 100,000 flying hours.
The frequency of accidents was relatively low.
It's your only airborne short time.
So your exposure is greater on takeoff and landing than it is at any other time.
You could take a V-52 and keep it up for 20 to 30 hours and only be exposed to one landing and one takeoff.
Sure.
Whereas if you took a fighter airplane, you'd have about 30 missions.
Sure.
that's 30 take-offs.
That's a lot more exposure to the dangerous part of it.
And also you've got the reliability of an engine.
One engine versus six.
So you can, sure, your odds are greater.
What was your opinion then of the quality of the B-52 and now of its
Because there's been a lot of controversy about this, I think.
Well, the B-52, in the beginning, was a hell of an airplane.
And it could walk away from an F-86D, climb up the altitude.
The F-86D was not in the performance range that we have now.
But the B-52 was a good airplane.
But we need a bigger, faster, probably not necessarily bigger, but a faster and better airplane than the B-52.
We need the B-1.
And how do you feel about the cruise missile and the deployment of the cruise missile and the B-52?
I think we ought to have the cruise missile and the B-52.
Not build the B-1, but wanted to just put the cruise missile in the B-52.
And what was your opinion of that?
I think he made a mistake.
A big mistake.
It helped get him defeated, I think.
So, you'd want both then?
Yes.
You want the B-1 and the cruise missile in the B-52?
I think we need them both.
Okay, now just explain to the layman himself what's the advantage of the B-1, besides speed?
Penetration.
Penetration.
You can send all the missiles over where you want to, but once you program them, that's all they got.
Once you program them, you have no control.
Sure.
When you send a V1, you've got full control.
And you've also got a computer in there that can think, not just react.
A guy can change.
He can alter.
He can alter his ultimate target or mission.
Sure.
Hold it.
And if something happens, he has the proper procedures to follow.
So more flexibility.
More flexibility and more capability.
OK. OK. Now, were you sorry that you left the command of the training, or were you ready to leave that?
I was sorry to leave that command, very much so.
I let it be known that I'd rather stay there, but they said,
We want you down here.
And then you came down to Randolph Air Force Base, but only for about five months.
No, I was there about a year and a half.
Oh, I'm sorry.
You're right.
You were there from February 56 to August 57.
And what was your job there?
Director of Crew Training.
I wrote the syllabuses for all the crew training.
We had the F-86D.
So this is basically a promotion, wasn't it?
Well, yeah.
Because now you, as the director of crew training, you're not just the commander of one of the training groups, but now you're the director of a number of commanders?
Well, I was in charge of all the training groups for all the crew training air force bases.
No kidding.
We had the F-100, F-4, and...
We had the KC-97 rammed off.
We had the helicopter training.
We had the special weapons training, fighter training, bomber training, and special weapons.
And your job is?
and design the courses?
Yes.
So you're back in education again?
Well, more in training than education.
It's training.
You must have had a good-sized staff to help you.
I had three good-sized staff.
How many?
About 12 officers and airmen.
How'd you like that job?
It was a very challenging job.
It really was.
To be familiar with all those different training programs.
There was a great diversity of aircraft involved.
I would think so.
How'd you ever stay on top of that?
We actually had B-47 training.
I grew up going on a B-47 mission.
It was very, very

educational to get involved with all these different programs and then have to go up and training command and defend them and get the right number of days to just to help with the courses they always want to shorten the courses make them shorter we had to fight for all the
for the time you think they actually needed.
Now, who did you fight?
Did you fight politicians or did you fight... No, no, training command and ESEF headquarters.
Okay.
We'd have a yearly meeting with the training command headquarters with people from the Pentagon.
Have a lockdown drag out of time, how much time it took.
Get them
USAF to understand what it took to produce what they love.
It was interesting.
How could you ever become proficient on all the different
on training on all the different types of airplanes?
I couldn't.
No way I could, but I had people under me who were, who had done it.
So you selected experts on each plane?
I had experts in each area, too.
Were you given pretty much a free hand to pick these people?
Well, the director of personnel, if you had an opening, the director of personnel would allow you to get people you'd select from,
Or if you knew someone out in one of the bases.
For instance, if I knew somebody at Perrin and I wanted to be in charge of interceptor training, I'd get, I could, if they were available, I could get them.
Or they gave me, they'd send me folders and say you select which one you want.
What airplanes were the toughest for our pilots to
learn to fly, which ones have the highest accident rate?
Well, being tough to fly and high accident rate don't necessarily correlate.
Oh, I know.
I'm just asking you two questions at once.
Gee, it'd be hard to put that in perspective.
I don't remember which one had the highest action rate.
A lot of them.
I don't even remember which one had the highest action rate.
I do...
Things like when they were first checking out in the B-26s, they talked about one a day in Tampa Bay.
Oh, really?
And did you lose about one a day?
That's the way it looked like, but that's back when we were old, too.
We didn't know that.
We just got that rumor, I guess.
I really don't know which one I would select to be the hardest to fly.
Did you have more mechanical problems with one versus another?
Because, you know, this is a big question as far as... F-86D was a very complicated airplane.
And then it got more complicated, though, when we got to the F-105.
The F-105 was the ultimate plane for one guy.
And ever since then, every airplane has had two guys instead of one.
And that's the F-105 right there.
To do the complete mission, I'd have to say that was the hardest one to teach somebody to fly.
The 105.
The 105.
To do the complete mission.
Because you had to do it all yourself.
And it included low-level navigation.
high-level navigation, and atomic bomb delivery, and gunnery, and rocketry, bombing, a whole smidge of everything.
